      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement was not a monolithic group; it was a coalition of diverse factions with conflicting strategies, most notably the \"Freedom Rides\" and the \"Freedom Summer\" campaigns. While some leaders like Martin Luther King Jr. advocated for nonviolent direct action, others like Malcolm X and the Black Panther Party pushed for self-defense and community empowerment. Despite these ideological differences, the movement succeeded because it united across these lines to dismantle institutional racism through both legal and grassroots pressure.",
